12.title: Setup
12.body:
GAME SETUP IN TABLETOP SIM

Reccomend use of setup script to optimize setup.  Follow prompts in game chat and select appropriate buttons on controller.

If manual setup is preferred, delete script controller object and follow instructions with (Manual) label.

STEP 1: Select Player count and assign players to colors based on Player Count:

    Select player count in script. Assign players to colors:
    
    RED -- Rebel (2P Game) OR Rebel General (4P Team Game)
    TEAL -- Rebel Admiral (4P Team Game)
    WHITE -- Empire (2P) OR Empire General (3-4P)
    BLUE -- Empire Admiral (3-4P)

    Teams (hearts-spades) are auto-assigned for colors.
    
    Host: You must change the color owner of the unused color hands in 2P-3P games.
    To do this: Select in the leftside tool menu "Zone" -> "Hands".  RIGHT CLICK the unused hands (Teal and/or Blue) and change to the main color for that faction (Teal -> Red in 2P and 3P; Blue -> White in 2P only).

    (Manual): Ensure proper reb/imp reference mat is placed for the player count.

STEP 2: Decide Game Setup variant:

    A. First Game Setup -- Lore focused set starting positions for units, no starting action cards.         Leaders don't use action card abilities. Suitable for those unfamiliar with the cards/game.

    B. Advanced Rules Setup -- Normal play of game with randomized starting locations and player chosen unit allocation.

    (Manual): Refer to Learn to Play manual for setup instructions.  

STEP 3: Shuffle all cards decks.
    
    Can click Shuffle button as many times as you want.

STEP 4:  Build Rebel Objective deck -- Phase II on III, Phase I on both.
    
    Auto builds shuffled reb objective deck.

    (Manual): Shuffle each different phase separately, then combine II on top of III, then I on top of II. Do not shuffle again.

STEP 5: (Advanced Rules) Set starting positions. 
    Draw probe cards until 3 rebel systems and 5 imperial systems (have rebel or imperial symbol) have been revealed.  Place Rebel loyalty in rebel systems.  Place Imp subjugation markers in the first two drawn imperial systems.  Place Imp loyalty markers in the last 3 drawn imp systems.  Return the 3 reb probe cards to probe deck -- delete the 5 imp probe cards or return to box.  Reshuffle probe deck.

STEP 6: (Advanced Rules) Imperials place starting units in starting bags near build queue in any combination of the 6 Imp systems (5 starting + 1 Imperial Capital) .  Must have at least 1 ground unit on subjugated systems.

STEP 7: (Advanced Rules) Rebels place starting units in starting bags in only the "Rebel Base" space and/or in 1 of the starting rebel systems.

STEP 8: (Advanced Rules) Use clean up script to delete starting unit bags.

STEP 9: (Advanced Rules) Each faction draws 2 Action cards from their Starting Action card deck into their action hand (Admirals' hands -- Teal and Blue).  Resolve any Immediate cards drawn.  Starting Action cards not drawn are discarded to Game Box/destroyed.

STEP 10: (Both) Rebel player secretly chooses location of Rebel Base by choosing from the Probe cards in the deck.  Probe card with location is placed facedown on Location area of Rebel Base.  In First Game Setup rules, location should not be adjacent to imperial units.

FINAL STEP:  Each faction draws 2 mission cards to compliment their starting 4 in mission card hand.  
    
    Use Draw buttons to draw cards to the proper hand.

Game begins.

13.title: TTS Nuances
13.body:
Several mechanics of TTS are used to improve gameplay.  There are also limitations in scripting/TTS that make for nuances the host/players must be aware of.

1) Setup Issues:
    
    Issue: Scripts currently can't modify hidden areas or hands.  This means Player Hands and the Hidden zone in the Assigned Mission card mat can't be modifed by scripts to prevent issues during load/setup.  Teams can't be assigned to colors unless a color is occupied by a player.

    Solution 1: Host manually changes player hand colors in 2P/3P games for some of the hands.  White/Blue are autoassigned team Spades.  Red/Teal are autoassigned team Hearts.  However, if the seat is unoccupied, that color is without a team, meaning the host must change these hand colors in 2-3p games.

    Solution 2: The Hidden Zone in the Assigned Mission card area may obscure the actual placeholder mat due to an issue during load.  To remedy, reload the save/workshop item.

2) Multiple Hands
    
    Multiple hands exist for each type of card.
    
    Imperial Hands: (from Imperial left to right)
        Probe Hand (General/White Default)
        Mission Hand (General/White Default)
        Action Hand (Admiral/Blue Default)
        Ground Tactics Hand (General/White Default)
        Space Tactics Hand (Admiral/Blue Default)
    
    Rebel Hands: (from Rebel right to left) -- Team 
        Objective Hand (General/Red Default)
        Mission Hand (General/Red Default)
        Action Hand (Admiral/Teal Default)
        Ground Tactics Hand (General/Teal Default)
        Space Tactics Hand (Admiral/Blue Default)

    Issue: The automatic TTS draw function (keys 1-10 or the right click prompt) does not work properly for all decks as cards will only go to the "Primary" hand of that color.

    Solution: Each deck has a DRAW button that sends 1 card from that deck into the proper hand location.  Note that the Probe Deck DRAW button discriminates based on Imp/Reb player and sends to the proper hands based on who clicks it -- meaning both factions can safely use the DRAW button without revealing the cards to the opposing faction.

3) Assigned Missions Mat

    Issue: Assigning mission cards requires cards to be committed facedown at the beginning of a turns to be used later.  Sometimes it can be easy to forget/confuse which cards are what and there is currently no 'peek' function in TTS to glance at the face of the card without revealing or taking back into hand.

    Solution: A Red (Rebel) and Black (Imperial) mat have been added to aid in placement of assigned missions along with a small Hidden Zone.

    This mat has several placement areas.

    Leaders:  Assigned Leaders (1-2) are placed in the Leaders Box to signal to the opposing player that a mission is assigned in that slot and who is assigned -- regardless of whether the assigned mission card is hidden or not.

    Assigned Mission Card (unrevealed): The area with a faded back image of the card. This snap point slot is for a unrevealed mission card to be placed.  By default you should place face down so as to not reveal the card while in transit from hand to placement.  Once the card is securely snapped to in the unrevealed slot, the player may use the "F" key to flip the card to face up for referencing the card.  This card will remain hidden to the opponent even during the flip animation.

    Revealed Mission Card: The area slightly forward of the unrevealed area with a faded image of the front details of the card.  This snap point slot is for Mission cards to be revealed to the opponent.  Simply move card forward and flip (if needed) and card will leave hidden zone and be revealed to opponent.

4) Imperial Probes

    The Imperial player can be slowed down by the mnemonic bookkeeping of current probe cards drawn.  The aid on the lefthand side of the Imperial board allows more efficient bookkeeping.  The area is hidden from opponent (to include cursers/pointers -- but not tabbed 'pings').  Use the custom tokens in the bag on the Coruscant space to place on the relevant systems.  An image of the probe card is used to denote systems probed while an imperial symbol on the reverse side is used to denote systems merely cleared by imperial presence.

5) Battleboard
    
    A battle board is on side of table to help with complicated battles.  Areas for each theater of combat and casualties are on board.  Additionally, tactics cards are drawn into seperate hands for theaters near board -- and copies of the unit reference mat have been added near the board to serve as local reference for attack/defend stats of each unit.

    Reset Tactics Card button is a quick way to reset the tactics decks after a battle.  In order to avoid issue, ensure each player discards tactics cards in the proper location (in snap points immediately under the DRAW buttons for each respective deck and faction.)  The player can inadvertantly do things to mess up script for reset.  If each deck does not have 15 cards after reset, then you will have to manually fix.

6) Auto-Dice

    Dice rolling can be tedious but the real dice have been included as an option.

    Auto Dice rollers have been made for both combat and mission rolls.  Use a math random function. Results are printed in game chat.  

    Reports: If results in game chat do not appear intuitive, try resizing the chat window to allow formatting of printout to make sense.  Optionally disable "auto hide chat" function in settings of chat window to prevent reports from hiding.  Reports are assigned a unique global ID number and report the player that rolled.

    Combat Rolls: (By Battle Board) Differentiates by Black and Red and separates based on Miss (blank), Special, Hit, and  Direct Hit symbols.  These are totalled by type and not combined together.  Use in combat rolls and for any specific dice rolls that require a distinction between Hit and Direct Hit.  Max of 5 dice per color per rules.

    Mission Rolls: (Under Faction Reference Mat in Center of each player area). Does not differentiate by black/red.  Reports Failures (blank), +1 Successes (Hits and Direct Hits combined), +2 Successes (Specials), and Cumulative Total of successes.  Max of 10 dice per rules.

7) Leader Rings

    In the real game, Leader attachment rings are snapped onto the base of the leader token.  

    For TTS, simply place Leader token on top of Attachment ring.  If you move attachment ring, the leader will go with it.

    For a sturdier handling of this, use the Joint tool to attach the Leader to the Ring by click-dragging it from the leader onto the ring.  This will make the two objects solidly attached.  To un-attach, use Joint tool to click-drag from the Leader token to empty space.

8) Discards

    Discard piles are located with snap points next to the respective decks.  Not all discards are supposed to have Discards though:

    Probe Cards:  Probe cards are never discarded.  

    Imperial Project Cards: Projects are discarded separately from mission cards -- faded back image labled projects under Project deck is discard pile.
    
    Rebel Objective Cards:  Objective cards are never discarded.  Used cards are returned to the Game Box.

    Mission Cards: Used mission cards that do not return to hand are placed face up immediately to the left/right of the mission Deck.

    Action Cards: Action cards are never discarded.  Used Action cards are deleted/moved to Game Box.  Not drawn action cards (in advanced rules) are returned to the bottom of the deck.

    Tactics Cards:  Discard piles are immediately under the Draw buttons for each deck.  Tactics cards are reset after every battle.  Ensure cards are placed in proper discard piles or else script will combine the wrong theater cards together.  Each deck should have 15 cards after reset.

9) Component Limitations

    Markers such as sabotage, loyalty, destroyed system, damage can be copied and pasted if players run out of these tokens.

    Leader attachment rings and Units should NOT be duplicated as the component quantity of these items is intentionally limited by the rules.

function clearCasualties(clickedObj, playerColor)
	printToAll("Clearing Imperial casualty area.", {0,1,0})
	local objects = casualtyZone.getObjects()
	local crateGUID = {}
	local crate = {}
	local unit = {}
	local unitCount = 0
	for k, object in pairs(objects) do
		local unitName = object.getName()
		if unitName == "Damage" then
			unitGUID = object.getGUID()
			unit = getObjectFromGUID(unitGUID)
			unit.destruct()
		else
			for unitK, unitV in pairs(unitCratesTable) do
				if unitName == unitV.unitText then
					unitCount = unitCount + 1
					crateGUID = unitV.crateGUID
					crate = getObjectFromGUID(crateGUID)
					unitGUID = object.getGUID()
					unit = getObjectFromGUID(unitGUID)
					local params = {}
					params.position = {crate.getPosition().x, crate.getPosition().y + unitCount*2, crate.getPosition().z}
					params.rotation = {0, 0, 0}
					if unit.getName() == "Star Destroyer" then
						params.rotation = {0,180,0}
					elseif unit.getName() == "Death Star" or unit.getName() == "Death Star Under Construction" then
						params.rotation = {0, 90, 0}
						params.position = {crate.getPosition().x, crate.getPosition().y + 5, crate.getPosition().z}
					end
					unit.setPositionSmooth(params.position)
					unit.setRotationSmooth(params.rotation)
				end
			end
		end
	end
	printToAll("Imperial casualty area has been cleared.", {0,1,0})
end

    local hit_list = Physics.cast({
        origin       = pos,
        direction    = {0,1,0},
        type         = 3,
        size         = {radius,radius,radius},
        max_distance = 0,
        debug        = false,
    })

		local refined_list = {}

		for key, value in ipairs(hit_list) do
      table.insert(refined_list, value.hit_object)
    end

		return refined_list
end

						recruitCard[i].setRotation( params.rotation )

						recruitCard[i].flip()
					end

				end
				recruitCard[i] = {}
			else

function makeBtns(btns)
	local params = {}
	params.font_size = 200
	params.height = 400
	params.width = 3000
	params.scale = {0.5,0.5,0.5}
	params.color = {30/255,60/255,255/255,150/255}
	params.font_color = {240/255,250/255,255/255,245/255}
	params.function_owner = self

	for k,btn in pairs(btns) do
		for param, v in pairs(btn) do
			params[param] = v
		end
		self.createButton(params)
	end

function thereIsNoTry()
	--change into real core deck
	local decks = {
		objI = startDecks.objI.obj,
		objII = startDecks.objII.obj,
		objIII = startDecks.objIII.obj,
	}
	local pos = {}

	for k,v in pairs(decks) do
		pos[k] = v.getPosition()
		v.destruct()
	end

	decks = {
		objI = startDecks.realobjI.obj,
		objII = startDecks.realobjII.obj,
		objIII = startDecks.realobjIII.obj,
	}

	startDecks.objI = startDecks.realobjI
	startDecks.objII = startDecks.realobjII
	startDecks.objIII = startDecks.realobjIII

	coroutine.yield(0)

	for k,v in pairs(decks) do
		v.setScale({1,1,1})
		coroutine.yield(0)
		v.setPosition(pos[k])
		coroutine.yield(0)
		v.unlock()
	end

	--change into real xpak deck
	local objs = roteBox.getObjects()
	for k,v in pairs(objs) do
		if string.find(v.name, 'Objective I') then
			roteBox.takeObject({smooth = false, position = {100,100,100}, guid = v.guid, callback_owner = self, callback = 'callbackDestroy'})
		end
	end

	decks = {
		objI = startDecks.realroteobjI.obj,
		objII = startDecks.realroteobjII.obj,
		objIII = startDecks.realroteobjIII.obj,
	}

	startDecks.roteobjI = startDecks.realroteobjI
	startDecks.roteobjII = startDecks.realroteobjII
	startDecks.roteobjIII = startDecks.realroteobjIII

	coroutine.yield(0)
	for k,v in pairs(decks) do
		v.unlock()
		coroutine.yield(0)
		v.setScale({1,1,1})
		coroutine.yield(0)
		roteBox.putObject(v)
	end

	return 1
end

	local stack = {}

			params.rotation = savedTable[v.guid].rotation

			roteBox.takeObject(params)
			table.insert(addedObjs, v.guid)
		end
	end

	startLuaCoroutine(self, 'buildObjectives')

function buildObjectives()
	local baseObjs = {}
	baseObjs.objI = startDecks.objI.obj
	baseObjs.objII = startDecks.objII.obj
	baseObjs.objIII = startDecks.objIII.obj

	-------shuffle up
	for i=1,60 do
		coroutine.yield(0)
	end
	for k, v in pairs(baseObjs) do
		if v then
			v.shuffle()
		end
	end

	pos = {}
	rot = {}
	-------pick the xpak ones
	if version == 'rote' then
		for i=1,120 do
			coroutine.yield(0)
		end
		local cards = {}
		local num = 0
		local taken = 0
		pos = roteBox.getPosition()
		for k,v in pairs(baseObjs) do
			cards = v.getObjects()
			if string.find(v.getName(), ' I ') then
				num = 5
			elseif string.find(v.getName(), ' II ') then
				num = 4
			elseif string.find(v.getName(), ' III') then
				num = 3
			end
			taken = 0
			for i=1,#cards do
				if taken < num then
					if cards[i].nickname == 'Death Star Plans' then
					else
						v.takeObject({smooth = false, position = {pos.x, pos.y+i, pos.z}, guid = cards[i].guid})
						taken = taken + 1
						coroutine.yield(0)
					end
				else
					break
				end
			end
		end
		for i=1,60 do
			coroutine.yield(0)
		end
		for k, v in pairs(baseObjs) do
			if v then
				v.shuffle()
			end
		end
	end

	-- stack up
	for i=1,60 do
		coroutine.yield(0)
	end
	pos = {}
	rot = {}
	pos = baseObjs.objIII.getPosition()
	rot = baseObjs.objIII.getRotation()
	baseObjs.objII.setPositionSmooth({pos.x,pos.y + 2, pos.z})
	baseObjs.objII.setRotationSmooth(rot)
	coroutine.yield(0)
	baseObjs.objI.setPositionSmooth({pos.x,pos.y + 4, pos.z})
		baseObjs.objII.setRotationSmooth(rot)
	for i=1,240 do
		coroutine.yield(0)
	end

	--deal 1 card to reb
	local card = baseObjs.objIII.takeObject({smooth = false, position = hands.rebObj.obj.getPosition(), flip = false})
	for i=1,60 do
		coroutine.yield(0)
	end
	card.setRotationSmooth({0,0,0})

	stage3()
	return 1
end

function setupMissionDeck()
	missionQueue = true
	local gate = false
	while gate == false do
		for i=1,30 do
			coroutine.yield(0)
		end
		if rebMission ~= '' and impMission ~= '' then
			gate = true
		end
	end

	self.clearButtons()
	self.createButton(backgroundBtn)

	headerTxt = 'Please wait...'
	makeHeader(headerTxt)

	local pos = {}
	impMissionDeck = {}
	rebMissionDeck = {}
	pos = deckMat.rebMissionDraw.obj.getPosition()
	if rebMission == 'rote' then
		rebMissionDeck = getObjectFromGUID(startDecks.roteMissionRebROTE.guid)
		getObjectFromGUID(startDecks.roteMissionRebBase.guid).destruct()
	else
		rebMissionDeck = getObjectFromGUID(startDecks.roteMissionRebBase.guid)
		getObjectFromGUID(startDecks.roteMissionRebROTE.guid).destruct()
	end
	rebMissionDeck.setPosition({pos.x,pos.y + 1,pos.z})

	pos = deckMat.impMissionDraw.obj.getPosition()
	if impMission == 'rote' then
		impMissionDeck = getObjectFromGUID(startDecks.roteMissionImpROTE.guid)
		getObjectFromGUID(startDecks.roteMissionImpBase.guid).destruct()
	else
		impMissionDeck = getObjectFromGUID(startDecks.roteMissionImpBase.guid)
		getObjectFromGUID(startDecks.roteMissionImpROTE.guid).destruct()
	end
	impMissionDeck.setPosition({pos.x,pos.y + 1,pos.z})

	for i=1, 60 do
		coroutine.yield(0)
	end

	if rebMissionDeck then

	taken = 0

	startList = starterImp
	if useBaseFirstGame == true then
		table.remove(startList)

	end

	}

					deck.takeObject({smooth = false, position = pos[taken], rotation = rot, guid = cards[i].guid})

						end

		end

function findPile(zone, drawDeck)
	--Checks card zones for deck status
	local zoneObject = {}
	local objects = {}
	if drawDeck == nil then
		drawDeck = zone[2]
		zoneObject = zone[1]
	else
		zoneObject = zone
	end
	objects = zoneObject.getObjects()
	local isDeck = false
	local deck = nil
	local deckPossible = {}
	local oneCard = false
	local i = 1
	for index, object in ipairs(objects) do
		i = i + 1
		local type = object.tag
		if string.find(type, 'Deck') then
			deck = object
			isDeck = true
		elseif string.find(type, 'Card') then
			deckLastCard = object
			oneCard = true
		end
	end
	if isDeck == true then
		cardDeckTable[drawDeck].lastCard = false
		return deck
	elseif oneCard == true then
		if drawDeck ~= nil then
			cardDeckTable[drawDeck].lastCard = oneCard
		end
		deck = deckLastCard
		return deck
	else
		return nil
	end
end

		if cardDeckTable[drawDeck].bothFactions == true then
			if factionClicked == "Imperial" then
				destinationHandKey = "imperialDestinationHand_Guid"
			else
				destinationHandKey = "rebelDestinationHand_Guid"
			end
		else

		end
		local destinationHand = getObjectFromGUID(cardDeckTable[drawDeck][destinationHandKey])

		local factionRotation = {}

		end

		return

function reshuffleDiscards(cardDeck)
	--Replace exhausted deck with discards
	local iH = 1
	local deckIndex = cardDeck
	local isBothFaction = cardDeckTable[deckIndex].bothFactions
	local isTactics = {}
	local discardDeckZone = {}
	local iMax = {}
	local deckText = cardDeckTable[deckIndex].cardName
	if isBothFaction == true then
		isTactics = true
		iMax = 2
	else
		isTactics = false
		iMax = 1
	end
	for i=1,iMax do
		if isTactics == false then
			discardDeckZone = getObjectFromGUID(cardDeckTable[deckIndex].deckDiscardZone_Guid)
		elseif i == 1 then
			discardDeckZone = getObjectFromGUID(cardDeckTable[deckIndex].imperialDeckDiscardZone_Guid)
		else
			discardDeckZone = getObjectFromGUID(cardDeckTable[deckIndex].rebelDeckDiscardZone_Guid)
		end
		local deck = findPile(discardDeckZone, deckIndex)
		if (deck) then
			local iH = i + iH
			local params = {}
			local cardRotation = cardDeckTable[deckIndex].deckRotation
			local destinationZone = getObjectFromGUID(cardDeckTable[deckIndex].deckZone_Guid)
			params.position = { destinationZone.getPosition().x, destinationZone.getPosition().y + iH, destinationZone.getPosition().z }
			params.rotation = {0 , cardRotation , 180}
			deck.setPositionSmooth( params.position )
			deck.setRotation( params.rotation)
			deck.shuffle()
			if isTactics == false and tacticsResetting == false then
				printToAll(deckText .. " discards have been reshuffled and placed as a new deck. You may now draw from this deck.", { 0, 1, 0 })
			end
		else
			if tacticsResetting == false then
				printToAll("No " .. deckText .. " discards to refresh deck!", { 1, 0, 0 })
			end
		end
	end
end

function productionCalc(reportAudience)
	local reportAudience2 = reportAudience
	--function that tabulates production info into table
	--clear production tables
	imperialProductionTable = {
		{groundTri = 0, groundCir = 0, groundSq = 0, spaceTri = 0, spaceCir = 0, spaceSq = 0},
		{groundTri = 0, groundCir = 0, groundSq = 0, spaceTri = 0, spaceCir = 0, spaceSq = 0},
		{groundTri = 0, groundCir = 0, groundSq = 0, spaceTri = 0, spaceCir = 0, spaceSq = 0}
	}

		{groundTri = 0, groundCir = 0, groundSq = 0, spaceTri = 0, spaceCir = 0, spaceSq = 0},
		{groundTri = 0, groundCir = 0, groundSq = 0, spaceTri = 0, spaceCir = 0, spaceSq = 0},
		{groundTri = 0, groundCir = 0, groundSq = 0, spaceTri = 0, spaceCir = 0, spaceSq = 0}
	}
	--loop for changing production tables with conditional logic
	for sysProdCriteria, sysCriteriaValue in pairs(systemTable) do
		--determine if sabotaged or neutral
		if sysCriteriaValue.isSabotaged == false and sysCriteriaValue.loyaltyState ~= "Neutral" then
			local factionProductionTable = {}
			local productionTurnIndex = {}
			--determine rebel or imperial table
			if sysCriteriaValue.loyaltyState == "Imperial" or sysCriteriaValue.loyaltyState == "Subjugation" then
				factionProductionTable = imperialProductionTable
			elseif sysCriteriaValue.loyaltyState == "Rebel" then
				factionProductionTable = rebelProductionTable
			end
			--set turns to produce index
			productionTurnIndex = sysCriteriaValue.turnsToProduce
			--add leftunit
			local unitType = {}
			unitType = sysCriteriaValue.leftUnit
			factionProductionTable[productionTurnIndex][unitType] = factionProductionTable[productionTurnIndex][unitType] + 1
			--add rightunit
			if sysCriteriaValue.loyaltyState == "Imperial" or sysCriteriaValue.loyaltyState == "Rebel" then
				unitType = {}
				unitType = sysCriteriaValue.rightUnit
					if unitType ~= "None" then
						factionProductionTable[productionTurnIndex][unitType] = factionProductionTable[productionTurnIndex][unitType] + 1
					end
			end
		end
	end
	--execute report function
	productionReport(reportAudience2)
end


function productionReport(reportAudience)
	--function that reports to chat production
	--loop for each faction
	for f=1,2 do
		local factionProductionTable = {}
		local factionUnitLabels = {}
		local factionProductionByTurn = {
			{},
			{},
			{}
			}
		local factionTurnReport = {false, false, false}
		if f == 1 then
			factionProductionTable = imperialProductionTable
			factionUnitLabels = imperialUnitLabels
		else
			factionProductionTable = rebelProductionTable
			factionUnitLabels = rebelUnitLabels
		end
		--loop for each turn
		for t=1,3 do
			for unitType, unitNum in pairs(factionProductionTable[t]) do
				if unitNum > 0 then
					--sets reporting for this turn to true
					factionTurnReport[t] = true
					--translate unittype to unitlabel
					for labelKey, labelText in pairs(factionUnitLabels) do
						if unitType == labelKey then
							unitLabel = labelText
						end
					end
					--add unit to report
					addUnit = "          " .. unitNum .. " -- " .. unitLabel
					factionProductionByTurn[t][unitType] = addUnit
				end
			end
		end
		--load results to faction/turn specific
		if f == 1 then

	if reportAudience == "All" then

	--private report to only factions

function returnToHand(guid_1, guid_2, obj_guid, rotation)


	local zone = getObjectFromGUID(guid_1)
	local object = getObjectFromGUID(obj_guid)
	local type = object.tag
	local description = {}
	local cardsToHand = {}
	if string.find(type, 'Card') then
		description = object.getDescription()
		if string.find(description, 'Return to Hand') then
			table.insert(cardsToHand, object)
		end
	end
	if cardsToHand ~= nil or #cardsToHand > 0 then
		for i=1,#cardsToHand do
			local params = {}
			local destination_GUID = guid_2
			local destination = getObjectFromGUID(destination_GUID)
			params.position = destination.getPosition()
			params.rotation = {0,rotation,0}
			cardsToHand[i].setPosition(params.position)
			cardsToHand[i].setRotation(params.rotation)
		end
	end
end
